      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked, such that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance between them. This is unlike classical correlation, where objects can only be related through direct interaction or shared information. In the world of quantum mechanics, entangled particles behave as a single system, even when separated by vast distances, which is something that would never happen in the classical world. It's as if you have two magical, invisible threads connecting the particles, and if you tug on one, the other feels the pull instantly, no matter how far apart they are. This spooky action at a distance, as Einstein called it, is a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics and has no counterpart in classical physics.",
