    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein famously referred to quantum entanglement as \"spooky action at a distance\" because he found the idea that two particles could affect each other's state instantaneously, even when separated by large distances, to be counterintuitive and at odds with the principles of classical physics. He was skeptical of the idea because it seemed to imply that information could travel faster than the speed of light, which would violate the theory of relativity. The term \"spooky\" reflects his discomfort with the phenomenon, which defied his understanding of the physical world. Over time, however, entanglement has been confirmed through numerous experiments and is now a well-established and crucial aspect of quantum mechanics.",
      "source": "target",
